misc¶

attempt to find the size of some shape

In [16]:
a=pl.imread('data/images/carcinus.jpg')

def rgb2gray(rgb):
    return np.dot(rgb[...,:3], [0.299, 0.587, 0.114])

b=rgb2gray(a)

fig,ax=pl.subplots(2,2)
ax[0,0].imshow(a)
ax[0,1].imshow(b,cmap=pl.cm.gray)
c0=np.where(b>10,255,0)
ax[1,0].imshow(c0,cmap=pl.cm.gray)

im = Image.fromarray(a)
from PIL import ImageEnhance
if 0:
    enhancer = ImageEnhance.Contrast(im)
    im2=enhancer.enhance(5)
else:
    enhancer=ImageEnhance.Sharpness(im)
    im2=enhancer.enhance(5)

i=np.asarray(im2)
j=rgb2gray(i)
c1=np.where(j>10,255,0)
ax[1,1].imshow(c1,cmap=pl.cm.gray);

for c in [c0,c1]:
    nin=(c==255).sum()
    ntot=c.size
    print(nin/ntot*100)

fig.set_size_inches(4,4.5)
for a in ax.flat:
    a.set_frame_on(0)
    a.set_xticks([])
    a.set_yticks([])

cluster analysis of images¶

Image clustering using Kmeans

In [17]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import pylab as pl
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np

a=pl.imread('data/images/carcinus.jpg')
z = a.reshape((-1,3)) # flatten 1st 2 dims

NC=2
k=KMeans(init='k-means++',n_clusters=NC)
k.fit(z)
i2=k.labels_
i2.shape=a.shape[:-1]

NC=4
k=KMeans(init='k-means++',n_clusters=NC)
k.fit(z)
i4=k.labels_
i4.shape=a.shape[:-1]

fig,ax=pl.subplots(1,3)
fig.set_size_inches((9,5))
ax[0].imshow(a)
ax[1].imshow(i2)
ax[2].imshow(i4)

ax[0].set_title('original')
ax[1].set_title('n=2')
ax[2].set_title('n=4');
